    <section class="mt-20 pt-16 border-t border-hairline max-w-4xl">
      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink font-sans mb-8 text-pretty">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <!-- Q1 -->
        <details class="group border border-hairline rounded-lg bg-canvas overflow-hidden shadow-lvl1">
          <summary class="w-full px-6 py-4 flex items-center justify-between text-left font-sans text-sm font-bold text-ink hover:bg-canvas-soft-2 transition-colors cursor-pointer list-none [&::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
            <span>What is FICA?</span>
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-mute transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
            </svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="border-t border-hairline px-6 py-4 bg-canvas-soft">
            <p class="text-body text-sm font-sans leading-relaxed">
              FICA (Federal Insurance Contributions Act) is the U.S. payroll tax that funds Social Security and Medicare. Employees pay 6.2% for Social Security (up to the $168,600 wage base) and 1.45% for Medicare (no cap). Employers match these amounts, making the total contribution 15.3% on the first $168,600 of wages. FICA is separate from federal income tax and is required by law for all W-2 employees.
            </p>
          </div>
        </details>
          
        <!-- Q2 -->
        <details class="group border border-hairline rounded-lg bg-canvas overflow-hidden shadow-lvl1">
          <summary class="w-full px-6 py-4 flex items-center justify-between text-left font-sans text-sm font-bold text-ink hover:bg-canvas-soft-2 transition-colors cursor-pointer list-none [&::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
            <span>How is federal income tax withheld from my paycheck?</span>
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-mute transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
            </svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="border-t border-hairline px-6 py-4 bg-canvas-soft">
            <p class="text-body text-sm font-sans leading-relaxed">
              Employers use your Form W-4 selections — filing status, dependents, and additional withholding — to determine your withholding amount. They apply the IRS progressive tax brackets to your estimated annual income and divide by your number of pay periods. The goal is to withhold approximately the right amount so that your total withholding equals your actual tax liability, avoiding a large refund or balance due at tax time.
            </p>
          </div>
        </details>
          
        <!-- Q3 -->
        <details class="group border border-hairline rounded-lg bg-canvas overflow-hidden shadow-lvl1">
          <summary class="w-full px-6 py-4 flex items-center justify-between text-left font-sans text-sm font-bold text-ink hover:bg-canvas-soft-2 transition-colors cursor-pointer list-none [&::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
            <span>What is the difference between gross and net pay?</span>
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-mute transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
            </svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="border-t border-hairline px-6 py-4 bg-canvas-soft">
            <p class="text-body text-sm font-sans leading-relaxed">
              Gross pay is your total earnings before any deductions — your salary or hourly wages for the pay period. Net pay (take-home pay) is the amount you actually receive after subtracting all deductions, including federal income tax, Social Security, Medicare, health insurance, retirement contributions, and other withholdings. The difference between the two can be substantial — typically 20-35% of gross pay depending on your income and benefits. For example, a $75,000 salary with 5% 401(k) contributions, health insurance, and standard withholding may yield around $55,000 in net annual pay — roughly 73% of gross. This calculator shows you exactly how each deduction impacts your bottom line.
            </p>
          </div>
        </details>
          
        <!-- Q4 -->
        <details class="group border border-hairline rounded-lg bg-canvas overflow-hidden shadow-lvl1">
          <summary class="w-full px-6 py-4 flex items-center justify-between text-left font-sans text-sm font-bold text-ink hover:bg-canvas-soft-2 transition-colors cursor-pointer list-none [&::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
            <span>How does filing status affect my withholding?</span>
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-mute transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
            </svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="border-t border-hairline px-6 py-4 bg-canvas-soft">
            <p class="text-body text-sm font-sans leading-relaxed">
              Your filing status determines your standard deduction amount and which tax brackets apply to your income. Married Filing Jointly offers the largest standard deduction ($29,200 for 2024) and widest tax brackets, resulting in the lowest withholding for a given income. Head of Household falls between Single and MFJ. Using the correct status on your W-4 is essential for accurate withholding — using the wrong status can lead to significant over- or under-withholding. For example, a single filer earning $75,000 falls into the 22% marginal bracket, while a married filer with the same income stays in the 12% bracket — a meaningful difference in tax burden.
            </p>
          </div>
        </details>
          
        <!-- Q5 -->
        <details class="group border border-hairline rounded-lg bg-canvas overflow-hidden shadow-lvl1">
          <summary class="w-full px-6 py-4 flex items-center justify-between text-left font-sans text-sm font-bold text-ink hover:bg-canvas-soft-2 transition-colors cursor-pointer list-none [&::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
            <span>Is this payroll calculator a substitute for a CPA?</span>
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-mute transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
            </svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="border-t border-hairline px-6 py-4 bg-canvas-soft">
            <p class="text-body text-sm font-sans leading-relaxed">
              No. This tool provides general estimates for educational and informational purposes only — it is not tax, legal, or accounting advice. Actual payroll and tax calculations depend on your complete financial picture, including state and local taxes, credits, deductions, investment income, and other factors this calculator cannot account for. Always consult a licensed CPA or tax attorney for personalized advice. Verify all current tax figures at <a href="https://www.irs.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-primary underline">irs.gov</a>.
            </p>
          </div>
        </details>
          
        <!-- Q6 -->
        <details class="group border border-hairline rounded-lg bg-canvas overflow-hidden shadow-lvl1">
          <summary class="w-full px-6 py-4 flex items-center justify-between text-left font-sans text-sm font-bold text-ink hover:bg-canvas-soft-2 transition-colors cursor-pointer list-none [&::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
            <span>What is the difference between FICA taxes and Federal Income Tax?</span>
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-mute transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
            </svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="border-t border-hairline px-6 py-4 bg-canvas-soft">
            <p class="text-body text-sm font-sans leading-relaxed">
              FICA taxes are flat-rate payroll taxes that fund Social Security (6.2%) and Medicare (1.45%), split between employers and employees. Federal Income Tax is a progressive tax based on your tax bracket and W-4 filings.
            </p>
          </div>
        </details>
          
        <!-- Q7 -->
        <details class="group border border-hairline rounded-lg bg-canvas overflow-hidden shadow-lvl1">
          <summary class="w-full px-6 py-4 flex items-center justify-between text-left font-sans text-sm font-bold text-ink hover:bg-canvas-soft-2 transition-colors cursor-pointer list-none [&::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
            <span>What is the FICA tax cap for Social Security contributions?</span>
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-mute transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
            </svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="border-t border-hairline px-6 py-4 bg-canvas-soft">
            <p class="text-body text-sm font-sans leading-relaxed">
              Social Security taxes are subject to a wage base limit ($168,600 for the tax year 2024). Any earnings above this limit are not subject to the 6.2% Social Security tax, though Medicare tax has no wage limit.
            </p>
          </div>
        </details>
          
        <!-- Q8 -->
        <details class="group border border-hairline rounded-lg bg-canvas overflow-hidden shadow-lvl1">
          <summary class="w-full px-6 py-4 flex items-center justify-between text-left font-sans text-sm font-bold text-ink hover:bg-canvas-soft-2 transition-colors cursor-pointer list-none [&::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
            <span>Who is responsible for paying Federal Unemployment (FUTA) taxes?</span>
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-mute transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
            </svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="border-t border-hairline px-6 py-4 bg-canvas-soft">
            <p class="text-body text-sm font-sans leading-relaxed">
              FUTA (and state-level SUTA) taxes are paid solely by the employer to fund unemployment compensation programs. These taxes are not deducted from the employee's gross paycheck.
            </p>
          </div>
        </details>
          
        <!-- Q9 -->
        <details class="group border border-hairline rounded-lg bg-canvas overflow-hidden shadow-lvl1">
          <summary class="w-full px-6 py-4 flex items-center justify-between text-left font-sans text-sm font-bold text-ink hover:bg-canvas-soft-2 transition-colors cursor-pointer list-none [&::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
            <span>What are pre-tax deductions and how do they affect payroll calculations?</span>
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-mute transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
            </svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="border-t border-hairline px-6 py-4 bg-canvas-soft">
            <p class="text-body text-sm font-sans leading-relaxed">
              Pre-tax deductions are allocations (like 401(k) contributions, HSA savings, or health insurance premiums) subtracted from your gross wages before taxes are calculated, lowering your overall tax liability.
            </p>
          </div>
        </details>
          
        <!-- Q10 -->
        <details class="group border border-hairline rounded-lg bg-canvas overflow-hidden shadow-lvl1">
          <summary class="w-full px-6 py-4 flex items-center justify-between text-left font-sans text-sm font-bold text-ink hover:bg-canvas-soft-2 transition-colors cursor-pointer list-none [&::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
            <span>How does the W-4 form influence tax withholding?</span>
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-mute transition-transform duration-200 group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
            </svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="border-t border-hairline px-6 py-4 bg-canvas-soft">
            <p class="text-body text-sm font-sans leading-relaxed">
              The Form W-4 tells your employer how much federal income tax to withhold from your pay based on factors like filing status, dependents, and multiple jobs. Filing a new W-4 adjustments helps prevent tax refund surprises.
            </p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </section>

